english:
  title: In Response to Verses Left by Various Generals at Yao De's Residence at Huating
  author: Lim Wi-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Seeking willows and finding flowers, we arrive at the pavilion in the fields—
    After Du Fu, the copper water-clock marks the passage past the third watch of night—
    After Bu Yanrang, clear wind and bright moon have no price by nature—
    After Yongshuk, blue waters and green mountains hold ever more feeling—
    After Chen Chunyi, only with zither and wine cup do we entertain our cherished guests—
    After Yongshuk, let not the strings and pipes sound notes of parting—
    After Yongshuk, the realm of Wuling seems not so distant from the world of men—
    After Hu Cangzhi, peach blossoms bloom on the banks, brocaded waves arise—
    After Li Bai.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a poetic response poem (和詩) where each line builds upon classical allusions and poetic fragments, likely from inscriptions left by visiting officials. The attribution to classical poets after each couplet indicates the source of inspiration rather than direct quotation.
  - key: ''
    value: The third watch of night (三更) refers to approximately 11 PM to 1 AM in traditional Chinese timekeeping, suggesting a gathering that extended into the late hours.
  - key: ''
    value: Wuling (武陵) refers to the legendary paradise described in Tao Yuanming's 'Peach Blossom Spring,' symbolizing an idealized refuge from the mundane world.
